animal.description:
Brooke a beautiful puppy of about 9 months old is waiting for her perfect family. We believe Brooke to be a pit bull mix puppy but something in her causes her ears to stand up now. She currently weighs about 40 lbs and is likely close to full-grown now. Brooke loves to play with other dogs and would enjoy a dog friend to share her new home with. She's been doing great at the different playgroups she has been in. She's a loving dog who loves to hang with people but she does prefer her kids to be a little older. Brooke has been to an event and did well. Her leash skills are coming along. She is a pretty playful girl with a big heart. Sadly in her kennel, she doesn't come off as sweet, because it's stressful for her to be spending her puppy time in a kennel. Outside of her kennel, she is a wonderful girl! 

To add this adorable girl to your family please apply online at rosscountyhumanesociety.org. Her adoption fee is $79RCHS does not conduct DNA tests on dogs who enter our facility therefore we are unable to guarantee breed or breed mix. Information provided by shelter staff, volunteers, and veterinarians is used to give a best estimate as to a dog's breed make up. We do our best to inform adopters about the potential breeds for each dog.

We are a dog only facility so we do not know how most of our dogs will be with cats. Even if a dog is surrendered to us and said to be good with cats there is no way to be sure the dog will be good with your cats. We do have a 7 day foster-to-adopt program so that you can see how the dog interacts with your cats before adoption.

animal.description:
Luna Moon is 45 lbs, she is a short stout little pittie that absolutely loves people! She's energetic and fun and comes with a loud bark when she is overexcited. Luna loves her people so much that she doesn't like to be away from them when they leave so she needs to be crated so she doesn't tear anything up waiting for her people to come home. Luna is strong and likes to go full speed ahead on the leash, especially if she sees a dog. This is where she gets reactive and wants to bark loudly at the dog she sees, that coupled with the pulling is pretty off-putting to both dogs and people. This is why at this time we believe Luna would do better in a home as the only dog. Her new home would probably be best not to be apartments or condos where walking is the only option for bathroom breaks and exercise. Luna could use some obedience training along with learning to curb her impulse control and then she wouldn't be so much when greeting dogs, we think. Currently, Luna prefers to use her eyes to get to know new dogs rather than her nose and this only makes her intros more difficult. Luna Moon would be best suited for a family who just wants to add a dog to hang with at home, her reactivity (unless she goes through training) would make socializing in public difficult. Luna moon also doesn't think cats are cool either so no felines in this girl's new home please. 

We offer a 7 day foster-to-adopt program where you can take the dog home for up to 7 days to decide if it's a good fit for you before committing to adoption. 

If you are interested in one of the dogs in our facility, please apply online at rosscountyhumanesociety.org. Once your application has been screened you will receive an email with a reply. Once approved please contact the shelter at 740-775-6808 to schedule an appointment to meet the dog.RCHS does not conduct DNA tests on dogs who enter our facility therefore we are unable to guarantee breed or breed mix. Information provided by shelter staff, volunteers, and veterinarians is used to give a best estimate as to a dog's breed make up. We do our best to inform adopters about the potential breeds for each dog.

We are a dog only facility so we do not know how most of our dogs will be with cats. Even if a dog is surrendered to us and said to be good with cats there is no way to be sure the dog will be good with your cats. We do have a 7 day foster-to-adopt program so that you can see how the dog interacts with your cats before adoption.

animal.description:
Gemma was found last fall on the side of a road in the Arlington area, she was a tiny three pound at the time. Since then, she has come a long way while dealing with a diagnosis of inflammatory bowel disease. Gemma has gained a pound in the last few months and feels much better. Due to the IBD, Gemma will need to remain on prescription food, a steroid, an antacid- and possibly an antibiotic when needed. Aside from IBD, Gemma has two teeth left (one of which is about to fall out), she has a heart murmur, and a low heart rate. At this time, applications are being accepted for Gemma as a special needs adoption. Her adopter will need to understand that Gemma requires special care on a daily basis. Until the time that her perfect home is found, Gemma will stay with her foster where she is very loved and doted on.

If you would like to adopt a dog from Rescue Row please fill out an application at https://form.jotform.com/91767055990166 

*Please check your junk email folder if you do not receive a response from a Rescue Row member within 48 hours.

*You must live within an hour of the DFW Metroplex because we do trial adoptions and require a homecheck

*Our adoption fees are as follows (paid by cash or a check made out to Rescue Row):

 Dogs 12 weeks-6 months old: $300 adoption fee

 Dogs 7 months and older: $275 adoption fee

Rescue Row is a 501(c)3 (non-profit) all volunteer dog rescue organization serving the DFW Metroplex. We are dedicated to rescuing dogs in shelters, dogs in abusive or neglectful situations, and dogs surrendered by their owners because of difficult circumstances. We place dogs in loving, responsible, committed permanent homes, following a comprehensive adoption process, which includes taking considerable care in finding good matches and educating prospective adopters about the responsibilities and costs of bringing a dog into their homes and lives. Dogs in our care are spayed or neutered, microchipped, receive all appropriate veterinary care and treatment, and placed in nurturing foster homes while they await placement in their permanent homes. We assist dogs in distress without regard to age, breed or ease of placement. Dogs in the greatest need take priority. Finally, we strive to work with shelters and other rescue and humane organizations to develop a network of supporters and volunteers in order to create a better world for homeless dogs.

animal.description:
The sweet lovebug!

Why hello there, hooman! My name is Pabbie. I am a 1.5 year-old, male, Terrier/Hound Mix weighing around 28 lbs. I am here because The Animal Pad rescued me from a shelter called Imperial County Humane Society. I am mostly house/bathroom! I love walkies, I will pull on the leash to explore and tug if there is another doggo around, but my foster is teaching me. I have a scheduled neutering appointment. I was sick from my shelter days but I am getting better with some medicines and TLC.

I am honestly just a love bug. I love to snuggle and love head and neck scratches. I am pretty low key/relaxed and a great house doggo. I love going for walkies and playing with my toys. I am a fast learner and will do just about anything for a treat (unless I am distracted on a walkie). I am scared of being left alone and will need someone to really work with me at overcoming my separation anxiety. I sleep well in my crate and will even go in it when you are home, but I do not like to be left alone in it, nor in the house. I want to be around my hoomans all the time. I am a bit jumpy around new people and will bark at them, and I do not like fast or sudden movements. Give me a little time to trust you! Once I trust you, I will let you pick me up and touch my backside but I do not like it if I do not know you and I will let you know. I am very doggo friendly. I am desperate to play with other doggos. I have no experience with cats or little hoomans. Now on to what I loveCuddles and snuggles! I will totally lay my head in your lap and crawl onto your chest just to be near you. I also love sleeping upside down on my back, squeaking my Padres bat and playing fetch. I love mealtime and treats, and you can always catch me sleeping with my head propped up on something. My foster says Im adorable and so so sweet. I will go on any adventure with you but is also totally fine just chilling at home. I am always excited to see you and Im easily trainable. I already know sit, down, stay, come, and is working on shake!

My perfect furever home would be one where my hooman(s) are home all day. Maybe a doggo sibling would help so I dont feel alone. I would do well with a yard or without. I will need a good amount of exercise to help with my anxiety and to keep up with my appetite. I just need love and affection to help me get through my rough past. My adoption fee is $400 and that includes spaying/neutering, shots, and microchip. If you want to take me home, please fill out the form on the website here https://theanimalpad.org/adoption-application/

animal.description:
The happy Energizer bunny!

Why hello there, hooman! My name is Griswold. I am a 8-month-old, neutered male, Shepherd Mix weighing around 45 lbs. I am here because The Animal Pad rescued me from Mexicali. I am house/bathroom trained. I am good on a leash if held short. Since I am still adjusting to this new life, I can be a bit skittish. I just need time to trust and feel comfortable in this new life! It takes me a moment to adjust to new surroundings and new homes, but I am learning!

So I a 8-month-old pup who has overcome a lot of firsts in socialization with other doggos, getting in a car, playing with toys, climbing stairs and entering a house. I am very trainable and has learned to sit, stay, lay down and heel (fuss in German). I am very smart and eager to please. I love attention, going to the park off leash or on long walkies. I am also very good in the house, as I will entertain myself with my stuffed toys or lay down for a nap. I am fairly easy to get into my crate and I do not mind napping there while you are out running errands. If left alone in the house, guard any tennis shoes or clothing left in reach, Im still in that puppy phase. I am also a bit of a character and like to goose you from behind! As I become more comfortable in my environment, my playful personality comes out. I can be a bit skittish when experiencing new sounds outdoors and Im trying a new product called Adaptil, a collar with momma doggo pheromones, that is to serve as a calming agent. I have some notable Husky behaviors such as whining when I am excited or wants to play. I seem to have a sensitive stomach, so I am not given any table food, and hence do not beg. I love going to doggo beaches and parks! I get along especially with Labs The only interaction Ive had with a cat is with one that was non-reactive and not afraid of me so I just sniffed them. When it comes to little hoomans I am afraid of them. I will crouch on the ground and bark at them, they seem so scary Im not perfect! Lets move on to the things I love. Ball chasing, running with other doggos, chasing other doggos into the ocean but I do not like to swim. I love to be outside, be with hoomans and get plenty of exercise. Once I have had a long walkie or time at a dog park, I will come home and settle for a long nap. I sleep through the night and can hold my bladder. I will let you know if I am uncomfortable and need to go out.

My perfect furever home would be one with any active individual or family who have plenty of time to be with me. I love to walk, hike, run on the beach or be off leash at dog parks. I am very trainable and loveable. I love hoomans, just not little toddlers as I am still getting comfortable around loud sounds. Someone with a yard would be good and access to outdoor space. I am used to 60-90 minutes of exercise a day. My adoption fee is $450 and that includes spaying/neutering, shots, and microchip. If you want to take me home, please fill out the form on the website here https://theanimalpad.org/adoption-application/

animal.description:
Please go to www.yvpr.org/adoptions for more information and to complete an adoption application. 
Hi my name is Kora! 
I’m the happiest most energetic pup around. I enjoy being outside to explore and to chase my foster sister around the yard. When I’m not napping, you will find me playing with multiple toys at once while cuddled up in my bed. Be ready for puppy kisses, cuddles, and belly rubs because this is the way to my heart. I will follow you around all day and sit right on your feet. I love to lay my head on your lap while we watch our favorite  TV shows together.
I'm really smart and I am learning commands quickly as long as you have treats for me. So far, I know the vocal commands as well as the hand signals for “sit”, “down”, and working on “stay”. I am basically potty trained and will jingle the bells hanging at the door to let you know I need to go outside. I am crate trained so I will sleep in my crate all night long and will happily stay in my crate for short periods of time during the day while you’re out.
My ideal forever home will have a doggie friend for me to play with as well as a big yard with a secure fence because I can climb!
I was found on the Indian Reservation by a very kind man who helped me find my way to Yakima Valley Pet Rescue. We think I’m about 8 months old and I’ve been told I’m a Pit Bull Terrier mixed with Portuguese Podengo.
I love everyone that I meet and get along with other doggies, but I’ve never met a cat before.
I’m looking forward to finding my forever home! 


An application must be filled out and accepted before a meet can be set up. If accepted, you will hear from us within 72 hours. You will have the opportunity to ask questions before you meet the pet; an adoption may or may not happen at that time. We do adopt outside the Yakima area IF you are able to come to Yakima to pick up your adopted pet.  We do not have a kennel facility; all of our pets are in foster homes. Therefore, meets and adoptions take place at either our office or at a place chosen by the foster.   If a pet has 'pending' beside its name, an adoption is imminent. Please fill out an application anyway because adoptions don't always go through. Your application will be kept on file for 30 days in case you find another pet you'd like to apply for.  Thanks for thinking adoption and Good Luck!

animal.description:
Meet Korra last adventure puppies. 4 sweet little 8 week boys with a lab mix mama who appear to have a shepard daddy! Mama was facing euthanasia in a southern kill shelter before an incredible group effort saved her life! She had babies the day after arriving at the rescue!! She has been getting healthy in foster abd is now up to 58 lbs! So we expect the pups to be around the same size! 
These pups are so sweet smart and affectionate! They are going to complete some very lucky families! 

Return answered Questions/details with pics of home!
Basic
1. Full name of all household members and ages
2. Address 
3. Phone number
4. Email address

Key questions
1. are you willing to housebreak a dog? 
2. are you willing to work with a professional trainer and behavioral issues ever arise that are out of your wheelhouse before considering re-surrendering the dog to the rescue? 
3. do you understand that transitioning 
 a dog can result in behavioral issues such as pacing inappropriate elimination growling chewing defensive behavior aggressive behavior depressed behavior and that each dog will need a unique amount of time to adjust?
4. Are all the current pets in your home up-to-date on rabies? 
5. are you willing to join  our private Facebook group forever family to keep in touch and share photos?

Learn about you questions

1. Do you have children in the home? What ages?
2. What other animals live in the home?
3. Do you have a fenced in yard?
4. Do you own or rent? City suburbs or other?
5. What’s your family’s energy level? how would you describe your lifestyle?
6. What type of dog do you picture yourself with?
7. What do you consider the most important behaviors or characteristics in a dog you adopt?

Details
Hey there! Are you interested in a pup? All our dogs are dog friendly, kid friendly, and can be cat tested. They will be UTD medically and may have required return visits for more vet care based on their needs.
Puppies are $1000/dogs are $800
Spay neuter
Microchip
Rabies*1
Distemper* 1-4 
Lepto* 2
Bordetella if desired
Heartworm test-pets over 6 months
Health cert 
Fecal exam
Deworming unlimited until negative fecal 
Current on :Flea tick prevention and Heartworm prevention 
Starter food
Treats
Toy
Poop bag dispenser
30-45 min training session at your local petsmart
Exclusive petsmart Coupons including free over night stay in hotel and doggie day camp visit. 30% off first groom too! 
Access to Furever Family private fb group
*Collar Leash - if available 
Seasonal extras

Please note there is a $25 cancellation fee. We ONLY set up meets with aproved adopters. Also, we do not "hold" dogs for any length of time once an application is approved (example: vacations, moving, travel). Please only apply if you are truly ready *now* to bring a new dog into your home. If you come out for your meet, unless it is not a fit, expect to take your pet and supply package home to start your in home trial. 
If you do make an appt for a private meet and do not select a pet, a fee of $25 -30 mins or $50 - over 30 mins will apply for your private visit. 

To adopt contact  Furever2016@gmail.com 
To get started send in pictures of your home and outdoor space. You will receive an application and a telephone interview. Then it’s time to meet our pets at their foster home- often in Ambler. On that day you will meet your pet and take them home for an in-home trial period. Just to make sure it’s a great fit for everyone! We require each adopter to join our private Facebook group Furever Family to keep in touch!

animal.description:
Meet BROWN SUGAR! His name says it all... this very sweet and happy 2.5 year old adult dog loves to hang out with his people. Sugar is about 61 pounds and has a gorgeous rich brown coat with a spot of white on his chest and toes. Brown Sugar is adorable, happy, outgoing and loves to snuggle/get attention from his humans! While he settles down nicely to hang our with the family, he also loves to go for walks, play with his toys, and especially playing with his ball and his people outside. He also knows some basic commands. 

Brown Sugar found himself through no fault of his own in a rural North Carolina shelter. Poor Sugar did not understand why no one came to get him and he had lost the comforts of a home. PetConnect came to his rescue and has brought him to the Baltimore/DC area to find his new home that will adore him furever. 

If you are looking for a very sweet, happy dog who will greet you with wiggle butts and gentle "kisses", Brown Sugar may be the one for you. He adores people of all ages, particularly loves to cuddle, get pets, and will make a wonderful family pet that is happy to join in the activities. He seems to understand housetraining and appropriate chew items. He would be a great companion to curl up at your feet (although he may try to fit in your lap:)) to hang out on a cool winter evening. Brown Sugar is neutered, up-to-date on vaccines and preventatives and eager to find a family to love! The adoption fee for Brown Sugar is $350, which includes routine vetting, vaccines, spay/neuter, and heartworm treatment. 

***Please note that the first step in the adoption process is to complete an application so that we can discuss which dogs are best fits for you and for them. An important step in the process is to complete a vet check. Vetting of current and past pets is very important to us, thus we will be speaking with the vet(s) listed on your application to ensure that your current and previous pet(s) are kept up to date on vaccines (including rabies ) , spayed or neutered, maintained on appropriate monthly preventatives and examined annually by your vet.*** Complete an online application, and contact Robin at kinstondogs@verizon.net if you would like more information on Brown Sugar!.

animal.description:
Mom looks to be a small Staffie weighs about 25 lbs. She showed up in someone's yard very pregnant and the man who owned the property gave her food & water and looked after her as best he could, but she soon gave birth to 5 pups! Since he did not know how to care for a mom and pups, we were contacted and took the little family in. The breed of the pup's father is unknown (perhaps some kind of Lab mix), but we believe the pups will probably be bigger than mom; most likely at least 40 lbs or so. 


Please do NOT call or email. The first step in the process is for you to completely fill out the adoption application in the link below. If your application is incomplete, we will move on to the next one. 

Due to Covid-19 we are conducting the home checks virtually. So once you have submitted your application, please take photos and/or video of your home, front and back yards, fencing, gates, other pets in your home, where this pet would be sleeping, etc. Then compose an email, attach the photos, and in the subject line of the email please put "Your Full Name (as it appears on the application you submitted) - the name of the pup you applied for". This will help us to match your email to your application in our software. Send the email to sparkyandthegang@yahoo.com and infosatg@gmail.com as 2 adoption counselors will be reviewing them and one of them will contact you if you have met these conditions.

Please understand that we often get hundreds of applications for one puppy. As we are all unpaid volunteers with our own families, pets, and jobs to attend to, unfortunately it is just not possible to respond to every single person all the time. We do the best we can and appreciate your understanding. The more thorough you are in answering the questions on our application and in your "virtual home tour", the more likely it is that you will be contacted. :)

Apply to adopt Serenity at:
https://www.shelterluv.com/matchme/adopt/SATG-A-118

You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Violet is Sandy's sibling. About 1 year old, 9lbs, wheat color cairn terrier yorkie mix. Very timid and shy but also sweet and loving. Prefers a quiet home with lots of patience, these two babies need too be accepted for who they are, two lovely adorable little dogs with no training who have never known a stable loving home. Secure fencing required with a home/fence check. Low maintained grooming.
adoption fee:$250

Please read the following carefully before applying:

YOU MUST HAVE A SECURE, FENCED YARD TO ADOPT ONE OF OUR DOGS. PARTIAL FENCING IS NOT ACCEPTABLE. Please see menu under "adoption info" for an explanation.

As with most rescue/shelter dogs, he or she may or may not be housebroken, or at the least need a readjustment /re-training period. If you are not able or willing to retrain a dog with housebreaking in a gentle, repetitious manner please DO NOT APPLY. NEW DOGS REQUIRE SPECIAL HANDLING, TIME and CARE. MAKE SURE YOU ARE WILLING TO MAKE THIS COMMITMENT BEFORE APPLYING.

We require adopters to first fill out our adoption app online. You cannot proceed with the adoption without it. This application has been developed using over 25 years of experience. It helps the adopter and us to make only the beginning of a good match; please be advised that if you do fill out the application, you may not be suitable for the dog you are applying for OR you may not meet our adoption requirements.

WE DO NOT ADOPT OUR DOGS TO HOMES WITH UNALTERED PETS...NO EXCEPTIONS! WHY? CLICK ON SPAY/NEUTER ON THE LEFT HAND MENU.

animal.description:
GODIVA is a friendly little 1-year-old, 20-pound Hound and Beagle mix.

This wonderful young friend is as sweet as can be!

WHAT'S NEXT?

If you would like to meet, foster or adopt this pet, please fill out our online FOSTER/ADOPTION APPLICATION which can be found in the main menu of our website or at the bottom of this page - simply copy and paste the link into your browser. EASY PEASY!

Once we've reviewed your application, arrangements can be made for you guys to meet! It'll be kind of like a blind date!

***

This pet is spayed or neutered in accordance with our strict policy wherein all animals are altered prior to adoption. This pet is dewormed, current on vaccines, and started on monthly flea/tick and preventatives.

Animal Alliance's policy is that we will adopt dogs younger than 1 year old to families with children under 9 years old. We do not adopt dogs 1 year or older to families with children under 9 years old due to the unknown history of adult dogs. 

BY APPOINTMENT ONLY:  Meetings at our Adoption Center are by appointment only (no walk-ins).  An online adoption application is required and must be approved prior to meeting any animals.  Adoption appointments are set up by email by our Adoption Coordinator (no phone calls, please).  This process ensures our dedicated time to the animals in our care, as well as full attention to adopters at scheduled times.  

Prior to submitting an application, please see the Animal Alliance Adoption Process for adoption details.

To fill out an adoption application, go to:
https://www.animalalliancenj.org/fosteradoption-application/

If you'd like to donate to help with my treatments, you can call the SPCA at 803-773-9292. You can also donate directly to our website at www.sumterscspca.com or come in person to our shelter at 1140 S. Guignard Dr., Sumter, SC 29150. Woofs and Kisses... CICILY! PLEASE call 803-773-9292 after 11:00 AM if you are interested in this pet. If you receive a busy signal, try again. Our call volume has been heavy. EMAILS MAY NOT BE ANSWERED DUE TO THE HIGH NUMBER WE RECEIVE. Thank you!

animal.description:
TINY is a darling little, 2-year-old, Chihuahua mix.

He's super shy but VERY sweet!  TINY would love to be some kind person's lap dog!

WHAT'S NEXT?

If you would like to meet, foster or adopt this pet, please fill out our online FOSTER/ADOPTION APPLICATION which can be found in the main menu of our website or at the bottom of this page - simply copy and paste the link into your browser. EASY PEASY!

Once we've reviewed your application, arrangements can be made for you guys to meet! It'll be kind of like a blind date!

***

This pet is spayed or neutered in accordance with our strict policy wherein all animals are altered prior to adoption. This pet is dewormed, current on vaccines, and started on monthly flea/tick and preventatives.

Animal Alliance's policy is that we will adopt dogs younger than 1 year old to families with children under 9 years old. We do not adopt dogs 1 year or older to families with children under 9 years old due to the unknown history of adult dogs. 

BY APPOINTMENT ONLY:  Meetings at our Adoption Center are by appointment only (no walk-ins).  An online adoption application is required and must be approved prior to meeting any animals.  Adoption appointments are set up by email by our Adoption Coordinator (no phone calls, please).  This process ensures our dedicated time to the animals in our care, as well as full attention to adopters at scheduled times.  

Prior to submitting an application, please see the Animal Alliance Adoption Process for adoption details.

To fill out an adoption application, go to:
https://www.animalalliancenj.org/fosteradoption-application/

Prince is a 4 year old 24 pound cocker spaniel who found himself homeless when his owner passed away. This little guy is the sweetest, most loving and gentle pup. The family reported he is house trained, good with kids/cats/dogs, and knows a few basic commands. He is very loving and friendly. 
He will come fixed, chipped, vaccinated, and heartworm tested negative.

***If you are serious about adopting, you must first complete and submit an application on our website. We will not do anything without a completed application. Do not contact us through pet finder or emails us as All info is contained here***

Please be sure to read all about our organization before you apply to adopt. If you are serious about adopting you must complete an application on our website. There is information on our petfinder home page and our website www.phoenixanimalrescue.com . Our adoption fee for adult dogs is $450. We will not adopt a pet to you if all of your current pets are not spayed/neutered. This is a
non-negotiable policy.

animal.description:
Laura is a 3 ½ month old Labrador Retriever mix, weighing 16 pounds (on 1.29). She is healthy and has had her first set of shots. She is learning to walk on a leash. She came in as part of a litter of four. Laura is very confident, friendly, and outgoing. She's alert, active, and loves to play. Be aware that she's a puppy and chews and has sharp teeth and nails. Laura would do best to go to a home with a fenced in yard or to a large SAFE property where she can get the exercise she needs.
...................................If you would like further information or would like to request an adoption application, please e-mail us directly at hss@cablelynx.com. The e-mail link on Petfinder offers seldom works. If you request an application and don’t receive it check your spam or junk mail file. In your request please include your phone number.

This litter of four: Judy, Rudy, Amber and Ashley, were transferred to Pintler Pets by another rescue group on 01/16/2021. Ashley is the 'fuzzier' of the twins Amber and Ashley. We do not know what breed the father(s) of this litter could be. The mother was a Husky/cattledog arrangement. We are estimating that the pups were born the first week of December.  

All our dogs are spayed/neutered, de-wormed, vaccinated appropriate for their age, vaccinated for kennel cough, and micro-chipped. Puppies (under 6 months) are $225.00; puppies (6 months to 2 years) are $175.00, dogs (over 2 years) are $150 and senior dogs (7 years or older) are $60.00.

Our application is on our front page of Petfinder, on the middle, right-hand side under our logo. Please send adoption applications to either pintler_petsmt@yahoo.com or pintlerpetsrose@gmail.com

animal.description: Say hello to Shadow. This is a very sweet and loving Catahoula Leopard Dog who happens to be deaf. But that does not slow him down. He loves to cuddle and play in the backyard with his brothers and foster sister. He is still learning to walk nice on a leash and is on his way to being house-trained. He came to the resuce with his two brothers and they have been together every since. So he would do great in a home with other dogs he can play with. He prefers to sleep in the crate with his brothers. He doesn't like to be left alone. He is a great dog and will be an amazing addition to any family. He will need continued training as he is still a pup. His brothers are Knuckles and Sonic. **Located in Crestview, FL (transportation available)

animal.description: My name is Bella. I was rescued a couple months back and boy has it been amazing!! I was given the best foster Mom, she has the patience of a saint because even though I hate to admit it, but I have very bad separation anxiety. Here in my new foster home Ive learned so many things, like kennels arent so bad, I actually like it. Better be a strong one though cause sometimes I still feel the urge to try and break out. Old habits die hard. I love the great outdoors. I look forward to my walks daily, they help me not feel so anxious. I do feel the need to scale the wall and get out of the yard, but who likes being confined anyway?! I have learned so much already. Cuddles... oh man are they the best! Im working on all these other weird things like sit,stay, and come. Im a little to anxious and get to excited for smalls animals and children. I cant help but chase the cats Mom says its frowned upon but have you seen a mad cat... I just cant help myself!!
animal.name: Bella

animal.description: Lylo is a sweet, goofy guy looking for his forever person(s). He is house trained and has been well behaved at home while his foster is at work during the day. Lylo knows how to shake, sit, and fetch. Hes very smart...He learned to sit and wait at the front door when coming home from a walk until his foster says ok within a week of practicing!! Lylo loves to walk and sniff the world, but sometimes forgets hes got a human attached to his leash. He gets really excited when he sees other dogs or smells something really good, and will need someone strong and dedicated to continue to work on his leash manners. Lylo would do best in a home without cats, kids, or other dogs (he likes to be the center of attention!), but he wouldnt mind some doggy play dates. Lylo is currently residing in Phoenix, AZ.

animal.description:
Mayflower is an extremely sweet dog. She has not shown any aggression toawrds anyone or anythig.

 Mayflower has not had any accidents since being w/us except the 1st nght which was very stressfulfor her. She is crate trained and seems to know right from wrong. She was an AMAZING mama to her 10 puppies. Mayflower has not responded to basic commands, but we will attempt to work on those once puppies have a home. ****She LOVES my 2 Great Danes, a home with another dog would be a wonderful thing for her and help her come out of her shell*****

------Cats-----This one is a caution, she pays no attentione to my 10yr big white fluff ball. BUT my 3mo kitten is another story, thanks to my own dog always playing with the kitten, Mayflower became extemely interested in her and we had an accident where she played to rough. I personally would only expose to adult cats, becasue i think she now thinks kittens are to played with and she doesn't know her own strength.

 Since Mayflower has arrived I can tell she definitely did not have a great start. The sweet girl is afraid of everything!! When she is outside she keeps her distnace from everyone, except me (that took a week) and at times she will reverts back to her instincts to run. Having the other dogs helped a LOT w/her learning to trust me. She has started getting on the couch with the dogs and me. When she is laying around inside she does let my 6yo daughter calmly come up to her and give her love, still keeps her distance oterwise, but kids are loud haha. Mayflower is still not sure what to think of my husband because he has not been around her a lot, but he can pet her when shes laying around inside the house. **after 3wks I am still the only one that can approach her outside***

When you choose to add Mayflower to your family, you will get an amazing dog, but you will NEED to give her LOTS of time to learn to trust you. I think having a dog will help.

He was scared of everything upon arrival but seems to be coming out of his shell.  This sweet sweet boy will do best in a home that has a fenced in yard, although could be adopted out without one if the owner is a person that can handle his size for a leash walk - which he does not like at all, so leash training will have to be on the list of things Charming will need.  He is very passive and because of his size, he will do well for an older family, or family with children over 10.

animal.description:
BABY OLIVE is 10 years old and weighs 108 pounds.

Well hello and good day to everyone out there. Since I am a dog bowl half-full kind of gal (as opposed to dog bowl half-empty), I am going to get the bad stuff out of the way right away.

For 9 years I lived with two other labs in a very small metal cage. Our owners would throw food at us, right next to where we peed and pooped, and we never got walked or really ever got out of the cage. There wasn't a covering from the weather so I really can't stand to be in a crate or getting left outside for a long time. Despite all that I am a happy and loving dog. In fact, that's why I was granted the appellation Baby, because I am a very big baby who only wants to snuggle and love. I'll take as much as I can get since my first 9 years were pretty devoid of any of that stuff. 

I love cats and people. snuggling is the best ever with them. I struggle a bit with new dogs, but once I get used to them it's A-OK. I sometimes display a bit of leash aggression when other dogs walk by, but just between you and me I think it's jealousy. Don't mess with Baby because Baby just wants to be loved. In full disclosure: my teeth are a bit worn, but they are all there - woohoo.

I am so sad to leave my current humans because they have taken such good care of me and taught me how to love again. I am really good at it now and am ready to show my forever humans.
 
INTERESTED in BABY OLIVE? The first step is to fill out our online Adoption Application (address link below)

NOTE: All of our dogs live in foster homes so it is not possible to setup a meet and greet prior to submitting an adoption application. Filling out an application doesn't obligate you to adopt, but it does save your place in line if there are multiple people interested.
 
ADOPTION APPLICATION (Type or cut & paste the below website address into your browser): http://www.sdroregon.com/adoption-application.htm
 
If our Adoption Coordinator determines you are a good match they will contact you. This is a great opportunity for you to find out more about BABY OLIVE and decide if you would like to setup a meet and greet.  
 
ADOPTION FEE is $150, and there’s a 10% Discount for Senior Citizens and Veterans.
 
Learn more about the ADOPTION PROCESS here (Type or cut & paste the below website address into your browser): http://www.sdroregon.com/adoption-process.htm
 
We apologize, but we are not able to answer individual questions about our dogs. We are a small, all-volunteer organization and we receive hundreds of inquiries. If you want to learn more about a particular dog, then please submit an Adoption Application. If your application is chosen, you will have the opportunity to meet the dog and to get answers to all of your questions. Thank you for your understanding.

animal.description:
Name Samantha
Age 2 years
Breed Husky
Spayed Female

Sweet Samantha was in a horrible accident. She was found on the side of the road where she had been hit by a car and left for dead. The wonderful family that found her worked tirelessly to find her help. After we rushed her to the vet he informed us that it had probably been 3 or 4 days that she was waiting for help after her accident. She was in great pain but all she wanted to do was lick everyone she met. She had to have surgery on both front legs and casts for 6 months. But during all that she still didn't lose her loving personality. She loves to hug and kiss everyone she meets. Due to the trauma she is shy of the harness (had to put one on to visit the vet every week, not fun, can you blame her?) But she is ready for a forever home finely. This sweet girl needs a home where she can rehab and grow into the wonderful dog we know she is. She loves to hug you or snuggle on the cough to watch tv. Like all huskies she is a talker but not a barker. Her foster family have put so much time, money and love into her that they want her to be someone's baby. Since she is a young dog and has husky energy (even though she can't go for long walks) she would not be good for a home with small kids, small dogs or cats.

animal.description:
1.7 year old Molly is such a doll! She is seriously the sweetest dog ever. We recently rescued her from The AntiCruelty Society downtown, where she spent a month and was a staff and volunteer favorite (we have already received messages asking after her!). She lived in one of the offices there because she is very different and terrified in a kennel setting. Outside of it she is happy, waggy, greets everyone, she is the best! So she is living in our staff office for now as well, until we can find her a foster home or a forever home!

Molly is housebroken and when she can't go outside because she is in a shelter not in a home, she knows to go on pee pads! She is so cute when she plays with and runs after her toys!

Molly was surrendered by her owner who could no longer care for her, and she is good with other dogs, but we do know that she should not be in a home with cats. She is great with all people, men and women. 

One other awesome thing about Molly is her size. She is actually quite petite! We think most of her weight is in her teats actually, she was clearly used to breed more than once :/ But anyways, she has dainty little paws and is knee-height. 

Molly will make some lucky person so happy! She will cuddle and show you all her gratitude. We love this gurl and know you will too, so please ask about fostering or adopting this gem today!

Hi, I’m Roxy and I'm looking for a best friend! I love people and I will be loyal; I like to know where you are, what you’re doing, and if I can help you. I am super sweet and lovey and I’m always so happy to see you. I wag my tail, wiggle my butt, and give the best kisses; I love to snuggle too! Beautiful, Aussie mix, Georgina just made her way to us from TX where this poor girl was being sold outside of a gas station. She was covered in fleas and ticks and was extremely sick. Georgina was taken to the vet immediately, where she nearly passed away from being so sick and upon her vet visit, it was discovered that she was also pregnant.

This amazing girl fought for her 5 beautiful babies and herself and managed to pull through it all. We were lucky enough to bring her to WI where we plan to find them all their loving forever homes. Are you one of those homes?

Georgina is approx. 2 years old and weighs around 45/55lbs. She is currently working on housebreaking and surprisingly does well on a leash. She is not currently crate trained but is learning that as well and will sit inside with the door open.

She is not very fond of cats so would prefer a home without them and does REQUIRE a fenced in yard.

Tiny Mochi is a Lovebug. He loves hugs and cuddles. He is a very fun and silly goodfball. He is a very loving and gentle baby, weighing only 5.6 lbs. He is 8 months old.
He loves children, gets along with all dogs and even doesn’t mind cats. He would be best with another dog at home to play with, or with children (over 8 years old), 
Mochi is very playful, but what he loves most is just to be held and cuddled.  
Mochi is not expected to grow  much bigger than he is. 
He is UTD on shots, microchipped and has been neutered. 

His foster says: 
“Mr Mochee is a puppy and with that comes boundless energy, this lil dude is a blast. He hobbies are fetch, chase, more fetch of squeaky toys or tennis balls. He can tell the time and knows when breakfast, treats and dinner is. Fetch or I nibble on toe's..or nap time.
He sleeps with me at night and likes to sleep by my feet or by back, he doesn't snore. Potty training has fun, he finally tells me he has to go outside then goes on the pee pee pads and outside..his perfect family would be active and have other dogs, he loves to play. He's just a awesome little bundle of love. So it's not all good, he's still learning people won't hurt him anymore, so he won't come when called, but sit down and he'll sit on you for a scratch. He also has a high pitched bark and isn't afraid to use it when you walk in the door or if something scares him (or if the other dogs bark) he absolutely hates the leash, but he likes his walking vest. He's food attentive so for good snacks he'll follow you. 
I hope this helps, he's so much fun.“

Dog's Name: Caleigh
Estimated Breed : Shepherd Mix
Approximate Age: 1-2 years
Approximate Weight: approx. 25 lbs
Currently Living at: Boarding
Adoption Fee: $300
DOG'S DESCRIPTION
Caleigh is a super sweet little girl who is maybe a bit unsure of her situation. She would love to join an active family. She is looking for a loving forever home where she can feel safe and secure.
Your new pet will require a refresher in house-training. K-9 Lifesavers strongly recommends all new adopters enroll their new pet into obedience training. This provides for an easier transition into a new home, ensures the dog remains well socialized, and helps form a bond between the dog and the new family.
Adoption fees cover basic vetting, spay/neuter surgery (for dogs over 6 months old), rabies, distemper/parvo vaccinations, treatment for worms, heartworm testing, monthly heartworm prevention and monthly flea/tick prevention (while the animal is in our care), and transport costs from high-kill shelter. Please note that on average, K-9 Lifesavers spend significantly more on each dog than their adoption fee. Adoption fee for HW positive dog also covers heartworm treatment at our partner vets.
Foster Program: Foster homes provide for the temporary care of a rescue until the dog is placed into a loving, forever home. For more information on becoming a foster parent, and our Foster Program, visit http://www.k-9lifesavers.org/foster/ or email our Foster Coordinator at foster@k-9lifesavers.org
Sponsor Me! Make a tax-deductible donation today by visiting us at http://www.k-9lifesavers.org/donate/ . Donations help us offset boarding costs and additional medical treatment for those dogs who need it. K-9 Lifesavers receives NO federal funding and survive with your generous support!
For more information on K-9 Lifesavers, or to view a complete listing of all our Adoptable Dogs, visit our website at www.k-9lifesavers.org.
Please "like" our Facebook Page for the most current events and new dogs.
Thank you for considering a rescue dog!

Ellie is a beautiful 1 - 3 year old 30 - 40 lb mixed breed dog that was rescued from an abandoned house in Oklahoma. Some of her breeds may include Miniature Pinscher, German or Australian Shepherd and/or Corgi. She's truly unique and is a sweet dog that aims to please. She gets along with the older children in her foster home and pays no attention to their cat. She's very shy and is always looking for reassurance that she's safe. Ellie has a very tough shell and is slow to warm up. She hasn't opened up to play much with her people or toys. She likes going for walks and rolling around in the snow. Loud noises and loud voices startle her and she will cower so a gentle voice will be needed to talk to her. She seeks us out to be petted and likes to lay at our feet. We enjoy having our animals on the couch with us so we've been encouraging her to sit beside us and this brings a smile to her face!

Ellie was rescued from a high kill Oklahoma shelter. She is approximately 1-2 yo mutt. Our best guess is that Ellie is Miniature Pincher/Chihuahua (...maybe some corgi or doberman or shepherd?).

If you would like to meet Ellie please complete an online application that can be found at: http://hopeanimalrescueofiowa.org/forms/196/dog-application

Ellie is a 4.5 month old spayed female lab/terrier mix who weighs 25 lbs. Ellie came to All 4 Paws after being advertised as "free" to anyone who would take her. We couldn't let this precious girl fall into the wrong hands and happily provided her a safe place to go. She is an absolute darling! Ellie trusts all and loves to get attention from everyone she meets. She is absolutely beautiful both inside and out - just look at that face! She has gotten along great with other dogs and likes to hang out with her friends. She wanted to play with the kitties she met, but respected their swats so we think she could live with dog-savvy cats with proper introduction. Ellie seems to be equal parts play and snuggle and promises to be a loving companion to the family willing to give her a chance. She does need some help with manners and not jumping up, so we feel she'd be best in a home with older children she wouldn't knock over with her love. Please help us find Ellie the forever home she's been dreaming of!

Interested in adopting? Take the first step and complete an adoption application on our website: https://www.all4pawsrescue.com/

animal.description:
READ BIO & APPLY at heartsforpawsrescue.com/adopt

Meet Kodi! 55lb neutered herding breed mix, 2 years 

Kodi was adopted last spring through HFP rescue. Due to a recent incident with a stranger while being pet (nipped), Kodi is in need of a new home in a quieter area. An active adult only home that will not require their dog to interact with strangers ideal. Kodi has done well meeting people but has certain triggers to sudden movements / handling sensitive. 

Kodi has also had instances of mouthing behaviors to adults/nipping. KoruK9 trainer was hired and Kodi made great improvements — owners were able to better predict when Kodi might get "revved up" and also divert his attention and calm his energy down. 

He has also learned lots of useful tools such as the "place" command and how to manage his intense energy & nipping towards us and other people. 

“I do think Kodi could be a great fit for someone that does not live in a densely populated area that does not have young children, and that has space to accommodate his energy.

He is a very affectionate, playful and loving dog once he warms up. He loves to play tug of war and to swim after balls thrown in the ocean.”

Check the words that best describe your dog.: FRIENDLY, PROTECTIVE, ACTIVE, PLAYFUL, SMART, AFFECTIONATE, OBEDIENT, ROUGH

Kodi displays herding breed tendencies towards fast motions which can include being pet and children running. He should go to a home without kids as he has made lunging motions at children running and playing.
He does nip when he's excited to see people(we think this is his herding instinct). This behavior is not aggressive - it comes from a place of being overly excited - but it does hurt and leave bite marks & bruises. We've been able to improve this behavior greatly and he does not do it with the same intensity he used to, but he continues to jump and nip when he's excited. Typically, he stops with a firm and assertive NO. We also use "Place" command to have him go to his "Place" and calm down, which has been effective.

As we described above, the most concerning behavior is that he did bite someone hard.. It did not appear aggressive, but rather just too strong of a reaction to an interaction/situation Kodi did not like.

Does the dog get along with Dogs: Dog-Selective

Kodi does not live with other dogs. But Kodi does have about 6 dogs he adores and is GREAT friends with. He loves to play chase with them and also a bit of wrestling. These dog friends range in size from 75lbs to 10lbs. 

I don't take Kodi to busy dog parks though as he does not do well with un-neutered dogs. And other, large, strong male dogs he can sometimes get a bit "dominant" with, and especially if there's another "dominant" dog in a group of dogs. But if there's an open space and just a few dogs that he comes across that are all neutered, Kodi has had a lot of fun playing with them.

Does your dog have handling sensitivities? How is your dog meeting strangers?: Kodi has typically met strangers with enthusiasm and excitement. He really likes people. He did bite someone recently who leaned over him and rubbed his ribs, so that seems like a trigger for him.

Does the dog like children?: No

Where does the dog sleep?: In my bedroom either in a bed next to the bed or in his crate (also in my bedroom).

Is the dog allowed on your furniture?: Yes

Is the dog crate trained?: No

Where do you keep your dog: He roams my home freely

: He sleeps in my bedroom either on his dog bed or in his crate (with door open)

How does the dog react to being left alone?: He seems to be fine. I do give him a filled Kong to give him something to do while I'm leaving and keep him occupied for the first 10-15 minutes that I'm gone. I have a camera to see what he's doing and he usually is just sitting or laying on the couch and really just stays there almost the entire time until I get back

Please list any particular fears your dog has.: fireworks

Desrcibe any training the dog has, tricks it knows, and any experience with a trainer.: Kodi and I have worked with a professional trainer. Focused a lot of time in learning various ways to divert Kodi's attention when he's excited, and finding ways to calm his energy down. He knows the following commands - Sit, Down, Shake, Spin, Look, Leave It, Heal. His recall has also improved dramatically and after a bit of training before letting him off leash, he's usually pumped to play and then come when you call him... I've been complimented many times at his recall. There are sometimes where there's a squirrel in the woods, or another dog that he's excited about where the recall is not the best, but he is getting much better with recall. He also knows the "Place" command and it's been really helpful to utilize this to calm him down if he gets overly excited. In general, if we want to initiate training, we say "Kodi, ready to work" and he immediately sits and pays close attention. Once training is over and we want to give him freedom to do as he'd like we say "free." He knows he's off the hook then. We also say, "Kodi, ready to play" and hold up a toy and he knows what that means. Then "all done" when we are done playing. Our trainer has told us that Kodi is a quick learner, but he is also stubborn and strong-willed.

Does the dog have any known health problems?: No

Does the dog like riding in the car?: Yes

What is the dog's favorite : He likes his orange rubber ball in the house and plays mini games of fetch in the house (outside, he loves to chase the ball, but does not bring it back). And he likes to play with his tug ropes. He also has a Benebone that he likes to chew.

His favorite activity is playing with his close dog friends and he does this at a nearby park that I walk to most mornings and also in the Oakland hills (in Redwood Regional Park, specifically). He also likes to just be outside. Sometimes we'll just sit in front of my house and just hang out in the outdoors. He also likes just being with his people. At night he loves to cuddle up between my girlfriend and I and just snuggle. Lastly, he LOVES the beach and playing in the waves and fetching rubber toys in the water.

What does the dog like?: He likes other dogs (especially his dog friends that he knows!!). And he likes his owners and owners friends who Kodi knows (he seems to remember people when seeing them a second or third time and gets excited to see them again). Kodi also likes squirrels. And he LOVES the beach - he loves to jump in the waves and fetch a ball or other toy. One of his favorite games is chase! He just loves when we chase him around the yard.

What does the dog dislike?: He does not like skateboards (although he's been completely fine with bikes). He also gets excited with motorcycles, the garbage truck and other large trucks, and I don't know if he does not like these things, but he seems to get excited around them, either barking or wanting to chase after them.

Does the dog jump kiddie gates or fences?: No

If yes, how high is the dog able to jump?: Kodi can jump quite high, but he's never jumped over a fence or a "baby gate" I have in the home.

Is there anything else you can share that is special, unusual, or endearing about your dog that will help the new owners?: Kodi is such a sweetheart! He genuinely smiles and is so full of life. He's affectionate, playful, and an absolute joy to watch play with his friends. When he's running free or playing with other dogs (or us), he's just as happy as can be. Before bed and in the mornings, he loves to snuggle and he's the type of dog that will lean in to you as you adore him. I love this dog. He's also super smart and curious. When he's experiencing a new sound, he tips his head to the left or right (so cute!). 

In the evenings, he does want to play, but if you are not ready to play yet (cooking dinner, finishing work or a chore, etc.) you can put him in his place and he'll calm down until you're ready to engage with him.

Are there any things you think a new owner needs to know?: He has done really well being off leash on hikes if there aren't a lot of people or other dogs around.

Please provide a summary of the “ideal” home for your dog:: Kodi would be a great dog for an individual or family that does not have young kids, that has dog experience and is committed to continued training, and is physically active and enjoys being active with a dog. He is excitable and struggles with impulse control, and would do best in a more rural or suburban setting. And even better if the person has a big yard for Kodi to run in and have play dates with dog friends.

Meet Jade! Jade is a gorgeous 5 and a half year old American Pit Bull/Hound mix with a goofy and energetic personality. This cutie absolutely loves to run around with you and chase after toys. She has done well meeting mellow male dogs. Jade is a sweet and fun girl who can't wait for a home of her own - if you're ready to make her part of your family, submit an application today!

animal.description:
1 year old Alfie was lying injured on the streets, when a good Samaritan brought him to a shelter to get him help. 
That saved his life, and being a sweet boy that he is, he won over his foster parents' hearts as soon as they saw his video. He was even more amazing when they met him in person. 

Alfie did not know what a bed was, and the first night, he slept by its side, after not being able to figure it out. 
Alfie gets so attached to his humans, that every morning, he waits patiently by his foster dad's bed, until he wakes up. 
He follows them everywhere. He loves to play with toys, and learn new tricks. 
He is great with children, and other dogs. 

He is healed now from the injuries he incurred, and his stitches are now removed. He will need dental cleaning every year until the vet thinks he is clear of his mouth injuries. 

We are looking for a home where he will be loved immensely, and his forever parents will take pride in his intelligence, and loyalty, 
He is such a great pup, and we only hope to find the best, most suitable home for him, where he will be safe forever. 

Alfie's adoption fee includes his transport cost from Texas to your state. If you are in state and will pick him up, you can save the transport fee.  

To meet this gorgeous boy in person or via facetime, please send an application via www.savesomesouls.com

animal.description:
“Ohana means family.” 

You heard Lilo & Stitch say it, but ohana has a deeper meaning than just family...

It extends from blood-relatives to “adopted” or “chosen” family.

So what better name than Ohana for this guy who just happens to have a tattoo of the Hawaiian Islands on the back of his neck.

Ohana has been with us a little while as we were gauging exactly what situation he would fit into best. ?

Here is what we have come up with, 

Ohana is a big ol boy with a tail that literally hurts to be hit by.
Tiny kiddos may not be the best fit because of this. 
Although he is a big sweetheart, he just might be a little to loving and hurt someone teeny tiny.

He does do well with more sturdy, respectful, children however and I think he would love some kids run and play and snuggle with.

He seems to be a lover of all humans so far.

He does super good with the cats here.

Dogs, he can live with, however he is a little bit quirky.

He is a dog that needs non-reactive dog friends.

He LOVES to play with other dogs, to the point it’s a little obnoxious at times, however he is not great with sharing high value things with other dogs.

Treats and food he can be snarky over if he feels they might get his, this is why a dog that won’t snark back is a must.

He also has a habit of taking toys from other dogs, so a dog that isn’t guardy of toys is also a must.

These habits are trainable and he has made leaps and bounds in the right direction, he just needs a home that can continue working with him on knowing there is plenty to go around.

Hana is crate trained and potty trained to a dog door.

HE WILL WORK FOR FOOD so training will be a breeze!

Treats = Life

We will be requiring a fenced yard for this boy as he had a tendency to go for adventures prior to coming to us.

He is microchipped. Neutered. Vaccinated. Dewormed. Up to date on preventative. Heartworm and tick born disease tested and negative. 

Also, just look at that Face!!

If interested in this good boy, apply here

https://form.jotform.us/82330533784154

animal.description:
Hi, I'm Delaware! I came from Alabama to Minnesota with my mama and 6 siblings just hours after I was born. 

I am one of the smallest in my family, and I am just ridiculously cute! My foster mama can't decide whether I look more like an otter or a seal - because I have this beautiful black/brown short fur that makes me look sleek, but I also wriggle my whole body with joy when I see people! I love to play and I love to snuggle. I dream of a family to call my own, and I just know there is someone who would love me, play with me, snuggle with me, and tell me how good I am (because I am!). Is that you?


--------------------------------------------


All our Warrior Dogs will have all age appropriate medical care and vaccines, a microchip, and spay/neuter before adoption unless age is a factor with a puppy younger than 6-12 months at the time of adoption. If that is the case, the spay/neuter will be covered in the adoption fee and the owner will be responsible to have the procedure completed at a Warrior Dog Rescue Veterinarian at the appropriate time.

Please note that the majority of our dogs in rescue are from shelters where they have been found as strays or abandoned. animal.description:
***Zeke is only available through our Foster to Adopt Program***


Hello everyone, my name is Zeke. As you can see, I am a beautiful soul. 

My life started out rather rough, but now that I am in the care of humans who love me, it's so much better! I had to relearn to trust, but I have realized that people are awesome! I am a pretty mellow pup and sure love my belly rubs. I enjoy going on walks with my family and do well on a leash. My foster family has another dog and a grade school aged child, that I am completely fine with. They love me too! I am about as sweet and gentle as they come, seriously! I have a secret, my foster family has not heard me bark. I have no reason to. I'm happy now! I would be happier in a home like yours though.... can we meet? 


FOSTER TO ADOPT:
Zeke just completed Heartworm treatment and is waiting for a negative test result which can take 2-9 months after treatment. During these months, he will need to make sure his heart rate is not elevated due to high energy play or exercise. Zeke is only available through the Foster to Adopt Program at this time. The commitment will be for an adoption but will be fostering until he is cleared with a negative Heartworm test result. All of the medical expenses will be paid for by the rescue while she is in a foster to adopt home, however, the foster to adopt applicant will be excpected to pay 50% of the adoption fee at the time they take the pup into their home to foster. Food, kennel, grooming and other supplies will be provided by the foster in the foster to adopt program.

animal.description:
NOTES FROM THE FOSTER FAMILY: Meet TALLIE...This precious girl, Tallie, has been surrendered back to our rescue due to no fault of her own. Sadly, her family dynamics changed and she was reluctantly returned after a year and a half. You can tell Tallie was well trained and well loved! She is a cuddle bug, be it on the floor, the sofa or the bed. Tallie is quite the athletic and loves to run. Here is the best part, if you call for her or whistle for her, Tallie will be at your side in a flash. The DNA has her as an Antolian Shepherd, Great Pyr and a small %of other mixed good stuff. She is so smart, she sits, lays down and is potty trained and  crate trained. She will be a great fit for active families, with or without another fur pup. Tallie does great with kiddos and other dogs that are very playful. She would not fit with an older dog, because of her playfulness. If you want to meet this special girl please contact us at info@tailsfromtheheart.org
#TFH #lookingformyforever

ESTIMATED DOB: 5-15-2019

Upcoming Tails from the Heart Meet and Greet events. CANCELED
For an application, please email info@tailsfromtheheart.org

With everything going on currently with COVID-19, we have canceled our public meet and greets until further notice. If you are interested in meeting any of our pets, please email us or fill out our online application. We can then review and send to the foster family. We may cancel our home visits as well but if you could attach photos of your yard and one or two of your home that would be great. In lieu of the visit this would allow us to meet you and allow you to meet the pet and conduct a possible adoption either outside your home or at a public place where safe distancing can occur.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.

Meet FRANCES! She's a mixed breed puppy who is just over 3 months old and weighs 25 pounds. Frances is an easygoing, easy-to-please girl - she just needs a chew toy and a ball and she's happy! She was found abandoned with her siblings in Texas but is now in the Northwest and loving life! She's endlessly sweet, a great listener, and gets along with dogs, cats, and human friends alike. She's fully potty-trained too! Frances will make a fantastic addition to any home. She's currently being fostered in Portland, OR.

OUR REQUIREMENTS FOR PUPPY ADOPTION:

1) PUPPIES WILL ONLY BE PLACED IN HOMES THAT HAVE AT LEAST ONE MEDIUM TO LARGE YOUTHFUL, PLAYFUL RESIDENT DOG that is age 1 or older. This helps integrate the dog into your household easier by giving the pup a mentor.

2) These puppies are not livestock dogs. They must be family pets that are allowed inside the home.

3) In addition to the youthful playful dog, someone must also be home at least part of the day. Please do not apply for a puppy if you are gone 8+ hours a day.

4) We give preference to applicants with prior Great Pyrenees knowledge/experience.

5) Secure and visible fencing required.

6) You must have a plan in place to socialize your puppy properly.

7) Please do NOT write us and ask if this puppy is available. If it is posted, it is available. However, we may be working other applications that came in before yours. If so, by the time you are approved, the puppy may not be available.

Adoption Fee: $425

All of our dogs are spayed/neutered, microchipped, heartworm tested and up to date on vaccinations.

Transport Fee: $300

Transport fee includes the cost of transport plus the Health Certificate required for USDA approved transport.

All of our dogs are spayed/neutered and up to date on vaccinations.

Adoption applications can be found on our website: www.greatpyrsandpaws.org

https://greatpyrsandpaws.rescuegroups.org/forms/form?formid=5959

Northwest adopter pays cost of transport to independent transport company. Transport is arranged by GPPR.

animal.description:
Breed: Lab mix
Sex: Female
DOB: ~04/20/2020
Weight: ~50 lbs
Energy Level: Medium
Personality Type: Happy, Social, Energetic
History: Owner Surrender/Transferred from another shelter
Good With: Dogs, Kids
Ideal Home: Active home with a yard. No apartments.
Fence Requirements: Physical fence required.
Special Info:

The information we are providing for this animal was developed based on observations and assessments in a shelter or foster environment. We do our best to provide information that will help determine if the dog might be a good fit for you. Please note that behaviors may change in a home environment. We also ask our applicants to assume that any animal they adopt from us will need to be potty trained and learn house manners, although this is not always the case. Our online animal bios are designed to provide as much information as possible and answer some anticipated questions. We do not have the resources to respond to emails with more specific questions.

We are receiving an unusually high number of applications per pet at this time! Please follow the rules below to ensure your application is reviewed; pay attention closely to these instructions because applications will NOT be processed if they are not followed. Please keep in mind that dog/cat availability is currently changing by the hour; you will receive an email if the animal you are interested in is no longer available. New dogs become available almost every day, so feel free to let us know if someone else interests you if your initial choice is already adopted! 

Fill out the application (DOG: https://www.iheartdogs.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/IHD-DOG-Application-9-10-18.pdf, CAT: https://www.iheartdogs.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/IHD-CAT-Application.pdf) completely. Every question must be answered, and it must be signed. If you are going to type your responses, open the application, save it, type your answers, and save it again. 

-Applicants must be 21+ years old and live within a 50-mile radius of our shelter at 22415 Groesbeck Hwy, Warren 48089.

-You must identify at least 1 dog/cat that you are interested in. If there are multiple dogs/cats, number them in order of priority. 

-Scan a copy of proof of home ownership (i.e. tax bill, deed, or mortgage payment - you can black out the account #, etc.) or animal clause/agreement of your rental agreement.

-Attach the application and home ownership proof/rental agreement animal clause to a new email and send it to bark@iheartdogs.org. The subject line must be formatted to read ""#1 choice of dog/cat, Your First and Last Name"". Example: Subject: Fido, Jane Doe
Once your application is received, it will be assigned to an Adoption Counselor who will follow-up with the applicant who is the best fit within a few days, or to discuss other dogs/cats. It could take up to a couple of weeks for you to receive a final disposition on your application so there is no need to check on the status.

-Introductions will be scheduled by appointment only, 45 minutes per appointment. The entire household, including current dogs, must be present for the appointment. The introductions will take place outside in our parking lot.

-We will continue to perform vet checks for current and prior pets in the household.

-Home visits will be in person for the yard and virtual for inside the home.

-Finalizing the adoption will also be scheduled by appointment.

While this process may seem cumbersome, it is interim during COVID-19, and it is designed to help us respond to the volume of emails we receive every day. Since we are receiving a high volume of applications, please be patient if a dog/cat is no longer available. 

Thank you for your understanding.

animal.description:
CLANCY is an affectionate happy dog about one year old. He is playful and friendly with people and dogs. He would love hiking, walking, running. He likes to poke you gently to ask you to pet him :-)

His adoption fee includes his neutering, vaccines, deworming, microchip. He was born on a reservation we work with.  He does still need some work with learning leash training. (He has a best friend ADDIE for your consideration - they came into the rescue together.) 

We have specific adoption and Covid rules listed below.

Revised adoption policy
Due to Covid -19 pandemic and social distancing requirements, we've revised our adoption policy. 

First, please email (desertpawsnm@gmail.com) to inquire before you fill out the online application to see if the pet is still available. (Please do not call or text). We'll send you a link to the application.

We are unable to do multi-dog/cat meetgreets or adoption events at this time or bring multiple animals to your house to choose from, so please only inquire if you're serious about adopting this particular animal. If you're just shopping around with several shelters and rescues, please let us know this. 

If your application is approved (which "could" take up to one week) then we will contact you to set up a Zoom chat or ph call to answer questions/clarify anything and set up a day/time to bring the pet to you. 

Since we can't come into the home/yard due to Covid-19, we ask that you send us pics /video of your home/yard/living area/current pets. 

We will discuss with you about meeting your other pets. At the meeting/adoption at your house (outside) please wear a mask (as will we), keep to a properly distanced social distance and have hand sanitizer and your own leash.

We adopt locally to Central Abq, Santa Fe, Los Alamos and Rio Rancho. No out of area adoptions inquiries please. 

The animals are fostered and our foster families like to know their fosters are happy, healthy, and cared for during their lifetime. We appreciate staying in touch periodically (just a pic, holiday card, social media, pics/videos  etc will make our work worthwhile :-))

Our volunteers and adoption board are working diligently with an overload of inquiries since Covid to match families and forever pets. Our workload on the reservations has also increased. We're sorry, but if you email us with questions that are already answered here or fill out an application that does not fit the parameters of our procedures we will not be replying to you. Thank you for your understanding on this!

Thank you - we look forward to hearing from you and having another furbaby united with a furever family!

animal.description:
"several bullets... birdshot all over"...

NOT YET TAKING APPLICATIONS - NOT YET AVAILABLE FOR ADOPTION

NEW INTAKE: Winky - male - approx 2-3 years old - 10.12 pounds - Terrier mix

"Several bullets... birdshot all over"... that's what the vet wrote who looked at Winky after he was brought in to the Ouachita Parish Animal Shelter. Did you know that in many rural areas and in some urban areas... animal control is not your local municipal shelter. Animal control is a human with a gun. In some areas, they won't hesitate to shoot-to-kill a dog or cat roaming on their property. There isn't any... "hey let's see if this doggie has a home... ". Nope... it's "get my gun!" That's exactly what likely happened in the case of Winky... a sweet-tempered sad little dog who thankfully survived and ended up in the hands of a good samaratan who took him to OPAS. OPAS took him to their vet for immediate treatment, held him for stray hold and then contacted us to take him in. He is currently at our vet for neutering, vaccinations, heartworm/fecal testing, etc., and we will have more information soon.

NOT TAKING APPLICATIONS: We are not taking applications yet. We will post when s(he) is ready for adoption. In the interest of fairness, EARLY application submissions will NOT be considered. Please note we cannot respond to messages/emails, etc., on dogs that are NOT yet available for adoption. Please wait until the dog is available for adoption. We appreciate your cooperation and understanding.

animal.description:
Hi i'm Jack and I am a big boy at 7 mo old who will steal your heart. I'm a healthy active boy, house trained and currently in a puppy board and train program to learn all of my good manners and obedience.  I am the VERY best snuggler on the planet! I also really enjoy the company of other dogs and would love to be in a home with another dog brother/sister of my own.. I am current on all vaccines, neutered, and microchipped.

At OCPBR, we do a foster to adopt with all of our puppies going to their new families. If you have another dog(s), the dog(s) must be completely friendly with puppies, other dogs and people. Please no senior dogs, puppies are young and energetic and need a playmate for their development. Plus it’s unfair to senior dogs to have to endure normal puppy energy. They must also be current on vaccines. The foster must be willing and able to participate in our foster care program to include, ongoing obedience training and socialization.

If you’re interested in Jack, please go to https://www.ocpbr.org/images/2019/08/OCPBR-Foster-to-Adopt-Application-2019.pdf and send in the app to adopt@ocpbr.org.

animal.description:
Just shy of a year old, this beautiful jumping bean of an Oreo-colored pitty mix is Julianna. The first thing you may notice about her is that someone attempted to make her look mean and tough by cropping her ears themselves. What they turned out with however were some goofy-looking jigsaw puzzle-like ears which are probably a more accurate reflection of this silly girl's personality. While I think we can all agree her ears would've been best just left well enough alone, Juliana is the type of gal that makes the best out of any situation. She is super fun, friendly, and outgoing. She's about 48 pounds full-grown and loves similar-sized canine playmates who want to wrestle and run around with her. Julianna has never met a stranger and she can't wait to meet YOU! So get in your adoption request right away!

Please note we are working with limited staff/volunteers at this time. For full details of our current adoption appointment policy, please see https://savinggracenc.org/adoption-appointments-during-this-time/. Highlights:

We are working with a very limited staff/volunteer base

We do not have the people power to respond to emails/call about specific dogs

Our appointments are limited to 2 people at a time and for a maximum of 30 minutes.

Please arrive at your appointment ready to meet the dogs we have available. At this time, many dogs are in foster families or not yet posted on our website. Be flexible and ready to meet any number of wonderful dogs available onsite at the time of your appointment.

All puppies and dogs at Saving Grace are crate trained, have been spayed/neutered, are up to date on their vaccinations, are on heartworm preventative and have been microchipped. Their adoption fee is $375.00. Each has been carefully screened for disposition and temperament in order to provide your home with a safe companion that will enjoy life as your new family member.

Our Adoption Form can be completed online at our website at https://savinggracenc.org/how-to-adopt/ .

An Adoption Form is required before setting up an appointment to meet with a potential adoptee or a foster home.

Sending an Adoption Form does not commit you to an adoption, it simply provides us with background information on potential homes.

If you'd like to donate to help cover the cost of care for these wonderful dogs awaiting new homes, please visit the donate page on our website at https://savinggracenc.org/donate-now/ .

Saving Grace is a small, non-profit 501-C3 organization operated by volunteers only. Most of our animals come from rural animal control shelters where lack of space and resources limit their time and adoption possibilities. Thank you for choosing Saving Grace! We look forward to helping you find your new companion and family member.
